What is a U.S. Person?


A “US Person” means:


        “US person” as such term is defined in Regulation S under the 1933 Act or,
    

        a person that is not a “Non-United States person” as such term is defined in Part 4 of the CFTC’s regulations, or
    

        a “Specified US person” under the Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act (FACTCA).
    

A “Specified US Person” for the purposes of the FATCA includes:


        a US citizen or resident individual,
    

        a partnership or corporation organized in the United States or under the laws of the United States or any State thereof,
    

        a trust if (i) a court within the United States would have authority under applicable law to render orders or judgments concerning substantially all issues regarding administration of the trust, and (ii) one or more U.S. persons have the authority to control all substantial decisions of the trust,
    

        any State of the United States, any U.S. Territory, any political subdivision of any of the foregoing, or any wholly owned agency or instrumentality of any one or more of the foregoing;
    

        or an estate of a decedent that is a citizen or resident of the United States,
    


